ce:section.ce:para:
The NTR responsiveness of Cu2-xSe@BSA@NTRP was assessed by a method described in a previous study [22]. In brief, Cu2-xSe@BSA@NTRP, NTR and nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NADH) were added to PBS. After incubation at 37 °C, the absorbance spectra of the reaction buffer were measured using a UV–vis spectrophotometer. To confirm that NTRP was released from the nanoparticles in a pH-dependent manner, Cu2-xSe@BSA@NTRP was placed in PBS at different pH values (5.5, 6.5, and 7.4). Following treatment for 1 h, the mixture was centrifuged at 12000 rpm for 10 min, and the resulting supernatants were analyzed using UV–vis spectroscopy to quantify the released NTRP. Additionally, in accordance with the above NTR-responsiveness treatments, the absorbance spectra and fluorescence images of the reaction solution were subsequently characterized by UV–vis spectroscopy and a fluorescence imaging system (IVIS Lumina XRMS Series III, PerkinElmer, USA), respectively. For fluorescence measurements, the excitation wavelength (E

                           x
                        ) and emission wavelength (E

                           m
                        ) were 520 and 620 nm, respectively.

Bacterial suspensions of E. coli and S. aureus were used to evaluate the ability of Cu2-xSe@BSA@NTRP to perform bacteria-responsive fluorescence imaging. A suspension of S. aureus or E. coli at a concentration of approximately 1 × 107 colony forming units (CFU/mL) was mixed with Cu2-xSe@BSA@NTRP at a concentration of 80 μg/mL (with an NTRP concentration of 10.8 μM). The mixtures were then incubated at 37 °C and shaken at 200 rpm in a dark environment. At different time points (0.5, 1, 2, 4, 6, 8, 12, and 24 h), the fluorescence of the mixture was measured using a fluorescence imaging system with excitation (E

                           x
                        ) and emission (E

                           m
                        ) wavelengths of 520 and 620 nm, respectively.
